  "prompt": "Why do electrons and protons attract each other?",
  "response": "Electrons and protons attract each other due to the fundamental force of **electromagnetism**. More specifically, they have opposite electric charges:\n\n*   **Electrons** have a negative charge (-1e).\n*   **Protons** have a positive charge (+1e).\n\n**The Law of Electric Charges:**\n\nThis law states that:\n\n*   Opposite charges attract each other.\n*   Like charges repel each other.\n\nThe attraction between electrons and protons is similar to the attraction between opposite poles of magnets. The force of attraction increases as the charges get closer and is described mathematically by **Coulomb's Law**.\n\n**Coulomb's Law:**\n\nCoulomb's Law quantifies the force between two charged objects. It states that the force (F) is:\n\n*   Directly proportional to the product of the magnitudes of the charges (q1 and q2).\n*   Inversely proportional to the square of the distance (r) between them.\n*   Directed along the line joining the two charges.\n\nMathematically:\n\nF = k * (q1 * q2) / r^2\n\nwhere:\n\n*   F is the electrostatic force\n*   k is Coulomb's constant (approximately 8.9875 \u00d7 10^9 N\u22c5m\u00b2/C\u00b2)\n*   q1 and q2 are the magnitudes of the charges\n*   r is the distance between the charges\n\nBecause electrons and protons have opposite charges, the force calculated using Coulomb's Law will be negative (if you define attraction as negative and repulsion as positive), indicating an attractive force.\n\n**In Summary:**\n\nThe attraction between electrons and protons is a fundamental aspect of electromagnetism and is due to their opposite electric charges, as described by Coulomb's Law. This attraction is what holds atoms together and is responsible for many chemical and physical phenomena.\n",
